issue_comment_body:
It is the expected behavior. 

GMP frequently has two functions for a given operation. There is a usually a function that accepts `mpz` arguments and a second version that accepts `mpz` and a native C long. When `gmpy2` parses arguments, it tries to take advantage of the two functions when an argument is a Python int.

The logic for mod(xy.) is roughly this:

```
if is_mpz(x):
  if is_python_int(y):
    if fits_in_C_long(y):
      retum mod_mpz_long(x, convert_to_C_long(y))
    else:
      return mod_mpz_mpz(x, convert_to_mpz(y))
  if is_mpz(y):
   return mod_mpz_mpz(x,y)
  do_other_stuff()
```
I just haven't added the extra check on the `is_mpz(y)` path.

Version 2.1 adds support for `is_divisible()`which uses a GMP function which only accepts a C long as the divisor. The performance is the same regardless of whether the divisor is given a Python int or an `mpz`.

If you are performing multiple divisions, you should try multiplying several divisors together and calculating the gcd().

Thanks for the quick reply!

I have log statements as follows:

    <<LOG Start of loop>>

    while(stale_x || stop_strategy.should_continue_search(x, f_value, g))
    {
        <<LOG Start of subproblem>>
        const unsigned long iter = solve_trust_region_subproblem(h,
                                                                 g,
                                                                 radius,
                                                                 p, 
                                                                 0.1, 
                                                                 20);
        <<LOG End of subproblem>>


        const type new_f_value = model(x+p);
        const type predicted_improvement = -0.5*trans(p)*h*p - trans(g)*p;
        const type measured_improvement = (f_value - new_f_value);

        // If the sub-problem can't find a way to improve then stop.  This only happens when p is essentially 0.
        if (std::abs(predicted_improvement) <= std::abs(measured_improvement)*std::numeric_limits<type>::epsilon())
            break;

        // predicted_improvement shouldn't be negative but it might be if something went
        // wrong in the trust region solver.  So put abs() here to guard against that.  This
        // way the sign of rho is determined only by the sign of measured_improvement.
        const type rho = measured_improvement/std::abs(predicted_improvement);


        
        if (rho < 0.25)
        {
            radius *= 0.25;

            // something has gone horribly wrong if the radius has shrunk to zero.  So just
            // give up if that happens.
            if (radius <= initial_radius*std::numeric_limits<double>::epsilon())
                break;
        }
        else
        {
            // if rho > 0.75 and we are being checked by the radius 
            if (rho > 0.75 && iter > 1)
            {
                radius = std::min<type>(1000,  2*radius);
            }
        }

        if (rho > 0)
        {
            x = x + p;
            f_value = new_f_value;
            model.get_derivative_and_hessian(x,g,h);
            stale_x = false;
        }
        else
        {
            stale_x = true;
        }

        DLIB_ASSERT(is_finite(x), "The objective function generated non-finite outputs");
        DLIB_ASSERT(is_finite(g), "The objective function generated non-finite outputs");
        DLIB_ASSERT(is_finite(h), "The objective function generated non-finite outputs");
    }

    <<LOG End of loop>>

When the process stalled the last time, the log was as follows:

	Start of loop
	stop_strategy.current_iteration is 0
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	stop_strategy.current_iteration is 1
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	stop_strategy.current_iteration is 2
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	Start of subproblem
	End of subproblem
	...

It never reaches `End of loop`. So I think it's safe to say that the [break](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/ca498ac2d214fd679f8c641f90d08fb63cac11f6/dlib/optimization/optimization_trust_region.h#L304) statement that you linked is never reached... At least not within a reasonable amount of time (the process runs out of memory a couple of minutes later since a buffer keeps filling up in the background while the main loop is stalled).

> But for some reason that doesn't happen on your machine?

Apparently, yeah. It's an ARM Cortex A9. The binary is compiled with GCC 5.1. Nothing too exotic.

> Are you sure the initial radius isn't zero?

Now that I have found the source of the issue, I will add additional logging statements. I can try to log the `radius` as well. However, it is a long and tiresome process since the stall only happens rarely.

Also, since the loop didn't break the first iteration, then `radius` couldn't be zero to begin with.

ok, so first of all I'm stumped that there's no API for forking a project! It's like one of the most basic feature to be expected from such a service 😖 And I hope that requests will land soon… BTW requests alone without a git ref that can be fetched is only half the feature…

That being said, it's a great job you've done 👍
but I'm not found of having everything as raw requests implemented in git-repo, because we're loosing the level of abstraction that an intermediate library provides.

I prefer to work on with a library that can gather more efforts from different projects implementing it to make it right, and eventually to maintain it when the remote API changes. And, then the `RepositoryService` specialization is just integrating that library for the special use cases of the project.

At the very least, if you want to roll your own API implementation (which is pretty clean overall), I'd then ask you to move it all within its own class:

```
class GogsAPI:
    def __init__(self):
        self.session = requests.Session()
        …

    def get_user(self, …):
        …

    def create(self):
        …

    def delete(self):
        …

    def iter_repositories(self):
        …
````

and then use that within `GoGSService`. Eventually, we might consider extracting that either to its own module in git-repo, or to a new library `python-gogs`.

@shuyangdu  no that's not what happens. Think of the list passed in the ``preprocessing_cases`` dict as one transformer (essentially a Scikit-learn pipeline), and all the estimators in the list under the same key in the ``estimators`` dict as all estimators applied to the transformed data.  Essentially like this:

```python
X_tr = X.copy()
for transformer in preprocessing_cases['case-1']:
    X_tr = trans_1.fit_transform(X_tr)

for estimator in estimators['case-1']:
    estimator.fit(X_tr, y)
```

Note that if you only have **one** preprocessing case, you don't need to create a dictionary but can pass the lists directly.

Sorry for the confusion, hope this clarifies.

